05304nam a22007815i 9780271077604DE-B159720210621102733.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210621t20212016pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97802710776047 a10.1515/97802710776042doi  a(DE-B1597)584531  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aHQ1595.A7 7aPHI0260002bisacsh04a305.420100aFeminist Interpretations of Mary Astell /ced. by Alice Sowaal, Penny A. Weiss. 1aUniversity Park, PA : bPenn State University Press, c[2021] 4cÂ©2016  a1 online resource (248 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aRe-Reading the Canon00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- t1 Locations and Legacies -- t2 Mary Astell and the Virtues -- t3 Mary Astell's Account of Feminine Self-Esteem -- t4 Mary Astell and the Development of Vice -- t5 Custom, Freedom, and Equality -- t6 Further Reflections upon Marriage -- t7 Mary Astell -- t8 "From the Throne to Every Private Family" -- t9 Mary Astell's Feminism -- t10 Mary Astell on the Existence and Nature of God -- t11 The Emerging Picture of Mary Astell's Views -- tReferences -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aOften referred to as a proto-feminist, early modern English philosopher and rhetorician Mary Astell was a pious supporter of monarchy who wrote about gender equality at a time when society tightly constrained female agency. This diverse collection of essays situates her ideas in feminist, historical, and philosophical contexts. Focusing on Astell's work and thought, this book explores the degree to which she can be considered a "feminist" in light of her adherence to Cartesianism, Christian theology, and Tory politics. The contributors explore the philosophical underpinnings of Astell's outspoken advocacy for the autonomy and education of women; examine the intricacies underlying her theories of power, community, and female resistance to unlawful authority; and reveal the similarities between her own philosophy of gender and sexual politics and feminist theorizing today.A broad-ranging look at one of the most important female writers of the seventeenth and eighteenth centuries, this volume will be especially valuable to students and scholars of feminist history and philosophy and the early modern era.Aside from the editors, the contributors are Kathleen A. Ahearn, Jacqueline Broad, Karen Detlefsen, Susan Paterson Glover, Marcy P. Lascano, Elisabeth Hedrick Moser, Christine Mason Sutherland, and Nancy Tuana.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Jun 2021) 0aFeminist theory. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Criticism.2bisacsh1 aAhearn, Kathleen A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBroad, Jacqueline, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDetlefsen, Karen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGlover, Susan Paterson, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLascano, Marcy P., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMoser, Elisabeth Hedrick, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSowaal, Alice, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSowaal, Alice, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aSutherland, Christine Mason, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTuana, Nancy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWeiss, Penny A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWeiss, Penny A., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn State University Press Complete eBook-